<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An overwhelming majority of Americans say they would buy organically grown food 
if it cost the same as fruits and vegetables treated with pesticides or 
synthetic fertilizers and nearly half would pay more, according to a new 
survey. The strong preference for chemical-free fruits and vegetables showed up 
in a survey conducted even before the recent scare over poisoned grapes from 
Chile and apples treated with Alar. The Louis Harris Poll conducted for Organic 
Gardening magazine found that 84.2% of those surveyed would choose organically 
grown food if given the choice, and 49% said they would pay more for organic 
food. 
</P>
