<HEADLINE>
<P>
CBS JOINS THE UCLA GAME BROADCAST LATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LARRY STEWART and 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since the North Carolina State-Iowa game went into double overtime, CBS had 
little chance of catching the start of the UCLA-North Carolina game. But was it 
necessary to miss the first 12 1/2 minutes? 
</P>
<P>
CBS went to a number of commercials and a report on Eddie Sutton quitting as 
Kentucky's coach before switching to the UCLA game. 
</P>
<P>
"We have business obligations," CBS spokeswoman Susan Kerr said in New York. 
"Commercials are sold as pregame spots, and so they must run before we can go 
to game action. 
</P>
<P>
"I think if we would have left the North Carolina State-Iowa game, a lot more 
people would have been upset." 
</P>
<P>
A Channel 2 spokeswoman said the station received about two dozen complaints. 
LARRY STEWART 
</P>
