<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
BOTHA OVERRULED ON MURDER TRIAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WINDHOEK, Namibia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Supreme Court today overruled South African President Pieter W. Botha's 
order to halt the murder trial of six soldiers charged in the stabbing death of 
a black activist. 
</P>
<P>
It marks the second time in four months that Namibia's highest court has 
overturned a decision by Botha to grant immunity to soldiers accused of murder 
in Namibia, also known as South-West Afria. 
</P>
<P>
A three-judge panel said the soldiers of Namibia's South African-led army will 
have to stand trial for the Nov. 30, 1986, killing of Immanuel Shifidi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA032089-0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 33881 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 20, 1989, Monday, P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 2; Column 6; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
120 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH COURT REJECTS PLEA BY SAN ONOFRE STAFF ON DRUG TESTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by workers at a Southern California 
nuclear power plant who are challenging their employer's random drug tests. 
</P>
<P>
The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that threw out, at least 
temporarily, a lawsuit attacking the tests. The justices already are studying 
the validity of drug tests in three other cases. 
</P>
<P>
The case stems from tests initiated by Southern California Edison Co. at its 
San Onofre nuclear plant. The tests, modified in December, 1986, require 
randomly selected workers to produce urine samples for laboratory analysis. The 
workers are told the day before they are tested. 
</P>
<P>
The plan was challenged by Local 246 of the Utility Workers Union of America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
